Worse is better, also called New Jersey style, was conceived BY
by Richard P. Gabriel in an essay "Worse is better" to 








                      to describe the dynamics of software acceptance, 
but it has broader application. 

It is the idea that quality does not necessarily increase with 
functionalityâ€”that there is a point where less functionality 
("worse <i>worse</i>") is a preferable option ("better") in 
terms of practicality and usability. 


SOFTWARE              Software that is limited, but simple to use, 
may be more appealing to the user and market than the reverse.